 BY LINUS CHIBUIKE THE British Government has concluded plans to return £4.2million to Nigeria, as part of recoveries made from friends and family members of a former Governor of Delta State, James Ibori. The British Government however said authorities were still working on the actual amount involved in the Ibori case. The British High Commissioner to Nigeria, Ms. Catriona Laing, disclosed this in Abuja on Tuesday, noting that the £4.2m was the first tranche of the funds to be returned. She spoke during the Memorandum of Understanding signing ceremony between the UK and Nigeria. The Attorney General of the Federation and Minister of Justice, Abubakar Malami, signed on behalf of Nigeria. He noted that President Muhammadu Buhari had said the returned loots should be deployed for the completion of the Second Niger Bridge, Lagos-Ibadan Expressway and Abuja-Kano Expressway projects. Details later… 